        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The spectral lines are about 200 km/s wide, so a spectral bandwidth of about 400 km/s as requested will confortably accomodate the line emission, while leaving line-free channels for the continuum measurement. The spectral resolution corresponds to 0.2 km/s and will be more than sufficient to resolve spectrally the individual sub-components. The main target of these observations is the CO(3-2) line, but we also incorporate the HCN(4-3) since it can be observed for free.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>These observations will detect both the sub-millimeter continuum emission from eta Carinae and its molecular line emission. The continuum at 345 GHz is known from previous observations (Abraham et al. 2014) to be about 0.2 arcsec across. The line emission, on the other hand, is expected to be composed of several clumps, each about 0.5 arcsec across. We wish to resolve these individual clumps, and therefore request 0.2 arcsec angular resolution. Even if the clumps are slightly more extended than expected, we do not expect any structure larger than 1 arcsec. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The line emission is expected to be at least 100 to 200 Kelvin. Thus, a sensitivity of about 10 K would be sufficient to provide more than a 10 sigma detection. We request a somewhat longer observing time to obtain a better coverage of the (u,v) which will help reach a higher dynamical range (see below). We note that improving the noise level from 10 to 2.5 mJy only adds 5 minutes to the total observing time, because the latter is entirely dominated by the calibration observations (the time on-source increases from about 2 min to about 7 min, but the total time only goes from 33.5 to 38.5 min). Evidently, the continuum of about 40 Jy will be extremely well detected. The spectral lines are about 200 km/s wide, so a spectral bandwidth of about 400 km/s as requested will comfortably accomodate the entire line, while leaving enough line-free channels for the continuum measurement.

We now address the issue of dynamical range. The requested sensitivity corresponds to a nominal dynamical range of about 4,000, significantly larger than what is offered in the current call for proposal. We note first that since our target noise is 10 mJy (and not 2.5 mJy; see the previous paragraph), the relevant dynamical range is really 1,000 rather than 4,000. In addition, in the case of the present observations, this will not be a problem because the molecular gas is distributed in clumps that are either displaced from the continuum peak, and/or more extended than the continuum emission region. The continuum emission at 345 GHz is about 0.2 arcsec across as measured in previous ALMA observations by Abraham et al. (2014). Thus, it will be essentially unresolved in the observations proposed here, and will only occupy a single synthesized beam. The molecular emission, on the other hand, is expected to be concentrated in several distinct clumps about 0.5 arcsec across. Moreover, some of those clumps will certainly be displaced from the continuum peak. For the central pixel, the peak line emission would be about 100 K (or 400 mJy) and the continuum will be 40 Jy. This corresponds to a ratio of 100 to 1, so the sensitivity may well be limited by the dynamical range for this central beam. Specifically the signal-to-noise will likely be set by the limitation on the dynamical range imposed by the bandpass calibration. This limitation is indeed evident in the ALMA spectra of eta Carinae reported by Abraham et al. (2014; see their Figure 2). However, all other beams in the image (where we still expect significant molecular emission) will be essentially continuum free. For these positions, the dynamical range could be limited instead by the sidelobes generated by the strong central continuum source. This is a much less severe problem because it can be mitigated by self-calibrating on the continuum itself. We will perform this self calibration on our data, taking advantage of the better (u,v) plane coverage enabled by the long integration time mentioned in the previous paragraph.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
